The first virtual operator will already arrive, this year, in the Czech Republic.
Probably
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite developed and our operators offer almost all services as their partners in Western Europe.
However, here we still lack something - the virtual operator, who would force those to be cheaper.
Probably won't be long enough to get there.
That Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe, we have already written it on mobile.cz.
The rest also confirmed this by the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTú) which warned that the price of SMS messages in our country is the most expensive in the entire Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of roaming fee regulation it is likely to reach a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators SMS sending from abroad will be cheaper than if sent from home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, lack of competition that you really want to fight.
This is probably paradoxical because we have three mobile networks and their high coverage is more than 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to regret that there is extreme competition in the Czech market.
The President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTú), Pavel Dvořák, also said that there is no place in the Czech Republic for any other operators.
It is perhaps true that for a classic operator with his own network he no longer has too many possibilities (for the rest, it would be very difficult to find some frequency).
However, there is still a possibility - the virtual operator.
Precisely the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile telephony market brought a remarkable price drop before which the classic operators also had to react.
At the same time, even before the entry of sharks such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile to the Britain market, voices similar to that were heard here and there.
It has been shown that there is room for such operators and that they can be successful.
On the other hand, there is no need to look for too far away examples.
In February of this year we informed you about the premiere of the Virtual Operator Mobilking in Poland.
Only after half a year, this operator managed to get over 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the neighbouring country.
On the other hand, after Mobilking is the Penta group which, apart from that, in the Czech Republic is the owner of U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility of focusing on many more specific target groups.
In addition, to enable them to function effectively, it is sufficient for many less customers than a classic operator.
They do not carry relatively large costs in construction, operation and maintenance of the network.
In the world this type of virtual operators are usually profiled with low costs - they offer cheap SMS calls and messages that however, it often counters with the most adjusted services supply.
Thus, for example, Tesco mobile in Britain offers at least half of cheap SMS with respect to competition.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a good blow to bet on a trivial target group.
This operator is specifically addressed to man.
"The right man chooses Mobilking - it's the operator who likes and whom you can trust," says David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, who works this virtual operator.
It is hard to say if I look like Poland's concept could get caught in our country.
The Vodafone spokesman, Miroslav Čepický, therefore doubted: "The Czech market is relatively small to access by segments on which most virtual operators are based.
Moreover from the point of view of the supply of services is relatively saturated"
In the Czech Republic there are no possibilities, say mobile operators
