The intelligent car imitates the flight of the beehive
What would be the best way to develop technologies in order to avoid collisions, if not the imitation of the obstacles sensors existing in nature?
For example, that of bees.
In a surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan, the beehives gave the starting point for Nissan engineers to design the next generation of the collision prevention system.
The Nissan, in cooperation with the University of Tokyo, designed the system of robotic driving cars type BR23C nature-immigrant, which was given to the characteristics of beehives, with the ultimate aim of creating a system that can do away with all collisions.
During the flight each beehive creates its own ovaled private space that actually looks very much like our safe capsule - explained in the Kazuhiro Doi exhibition, technological director of RP and development and research.
They play an important role in the composite eyes of bees that are able to see in all directions at an angle greater than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of the composite eyes, engineers used the laser beam length measurement system.
It identifies the obstacles in front of the BR23C within a distance of 2 meters, at an angle of 180 degrees, calculates its distance and sends a signal to the vehicle microprocessor that immediately turns into a maneuver to avoid collision.
In a fraction of seconds the obstacle is identified, then the vehicle robot imitating the movements of the beehives, modifies the direction by turning the wheels to the necessary extent.
Unlike any existing system, this maneuver is totally instinctive.
"If not, the robot of the vehicle could not react quickly enough to avoid obstacles" - explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the project of the vehicle robot.
It must react immediately and instinctively, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable inner layer of the safety protective capsule, in a layer within which currently all types of collisions are considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what a bee does to do away with other beeches.
This process must be carried out at the opening and closing of the eyes.
However, unlike the beehives, the movement cannot turn upwards, downs or diagonally, but can only be two-dimensional and exclusively in the turn direction of the wheels
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities that exist for bees to dodge other bees, here they only used as a possibility for the robot of the car the rotating movement and the acceleration besides the braking.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and their energy density is greater, which means that they have a longer life duration than that of lithium-ion.
According to Andoh, the important thing is instinctive and intelligent reaction and not data processing capacity, much less storage capacity.
This device in each second must only process some input signals and react as the case may be.
It is not necessary to store this data or react with an instinctive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, so it uses only a few tens of kilobytes of memory.
No gigabytes or megabytes are needed.
This is the first step in developing technology to immediately avoid obstacles, which according to Nissan's calculations, can be incorporated into serial-made models within ten years.
Another possibility for its application is to incorporate the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system to take the driver to their destination, avoiding the obstacles on their way.
