Industrial prices continue to rise
In August 2008, national industrial selling prices increased by 0.1 percent compared to last month's prices and by 12.9 percent compared to August 2007 prices - reported the Central Statistical Office (KSH).
Industrial export prices rose by 1.1 per cent compared to July 2008 and decreased by 3.9 per cent compared to the previous year.
And as a result of changes in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent compared to the previous month and by 3.2 per cent compared to the previous year.
Industrial sales prices increased only to a minimum, with 0.1 percent.
The domestic sales prices of the processing industry sectors increased at a minimum of 0.1 percent compared to the month of July.
The largest price increase occurred in August 2008 in the leather and footwear production sector (2.8%), due primarily to the increase of 4.6 per cent per month in the bags and belts and the increase of 2.5 per cent in the footwear sector.
The higher price of plastic and chemical-based materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in chemical-material production branch prices (1.6 percent).
There was a decrease in price in the petrochemical sector (1.4 percent), in the production of electrical machinery and instruments (0.9 percent), as well as - to a minimum extent - in the processing sectors of wood (0.1 percent).
The prices of paper production, editorials and printing prices did not change.
In the rest of the processing industry, there was an increase in prices between 0.2 and 0.9 per cent.
In the supply of electricity, gas, heat and water that represent an important weight within the internal trade, an increase of 0.3 per cent was recorded in August, primarily as a result of the increase in official prices from the first of July.
In a comparison of a twelve-month period - in domestic sales of the processing industry sectors - the largest price increase was recorded in the petrochemical sector (32.4%).
There was an increase of 13.2 per cent in the metal production sector, while in the food, drink and tobacco industry, of determining weight, there was an increase of 11 per cent.
There was a decrease in prices in the textile industry (2.5 percent), as well as in the manufacture of electrical machinery and instruments (0.3 percent).
In the rest of the processing sectors, the rate of price growth was between 0.6 and 9.1 percent.
Over the past year in the processing industry globally increased prices by 10.2 percent.
The electricity prices, the supply of gas, heat and water exceeded the prices of the previous year by 18.7 percent.
In August, among the different sectors of domestic trade, the largest monthly price increase (0.7 per cent) was recorded in the investment goods sectors.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, in energy and intermediate sectors prices there was no change compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, with respect to the same month of the previous year, the largest price increase occurred in the energy sectors and in the intermediate industry (16.8%).
In the producer branches of consumer goods there was a 6.8 percent decrease and in investment goods a 1.4 percent decrease.
The export prices of the industry calculated in HUF increased by 1.1 per cent compared to the previous month, and compared to 12 months, there was a decrease of 3.9 per cent.
The contribution of our national currency in one month was reduced by 1.7 percent with respect to the euro and by 7.1 percent with respect to the dollar, compared to August 2007 strengthened by 7.5 percent with respect to the euro and 15.9 percent with respect to the dollar.
