Goodbye to the old cinema Paradiso, the city cancels historic rooms
Historical cinemas close by favoring multiplexes.
"A city without cinematographic rooms in a blind city, is like a face without eyes."
The image offered by director Giuseppe Tornatore photographer effectively what is happening in the large Italian cities as well as in the cities of the province.
The process of marginalizing the cinemas, which with the birth of the great methics on the periphery and the consequent disappearance of the mono rooms in the central areas of the city, is an inevitable and indisputable event with all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear are almost always historical places, full of memory," it's as if a friend died, a known one with which a piece of place and so much emotion was shared," says the director of the new cinema Paradise, the film that 20 years ago won the cousin Oscar and the grand prize of the jury to Cannes, which counted the poetry of a cinema hall in the province and nostalgia for the way of living the cinema that may be lost forever.
The figures given by the Anec, the leading association of traders, speak clearly: in the last five years 316 traditional cinemas have been closed, and to pay the bulk are the rooms of the main cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 less in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most suffered by the closures are as first, Emilia-Romaña with 82 cinemas less, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
It is a demonstration that the responsible for its disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, it is the very three Italian regions that have registered the largest number of new methic cinemas: 195 screens more in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany than in Emilia-Romaña.
"The Italian exercise has been developed irrationally" notes Paolo Protti, president of the Anec, "it would be useful to build new structures but it would be necessary to ensure the permanence of those already existing, because when a city hall closes, not all its frequenters are willing to transfer to the meticones.
Not to mention the lack of funds for traders: the previous state debt is approximately EUR 10 million.
It is shameful from the ethical and moral point of view that the government does not respect the laws that exist.
To support the sector would serve between 16 and 18 million euros a year’.
Interesting the case of Bologna, the first Italian city concerned by the closures, decided to repair itself with the signature of a protocol between the municipality and Anec, the first of this type in Italy to promote and protect the cinema mono room is in the historical center that on the outskirts.
Among the proposed rules are tax facilitation measures in favour of managers and benefits to the public in terms of mobility: spectators may enter the restricted traffic area and will have special parking rates.
"It's an initiative that I like" observes Giuseppe Tornatore" and I hope other cities will follow the example of Bologna by setting up other measures.
It is true, that in contrast to the extra power of the meticones, traditional rooms have to improve the quality of sound and image because today the public is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is an issue that was always important for me: the closing of the cinema in Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to realize the "New Cinema Paradise", which I had been thinking about for 10 years.
I have been living in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass in front of the Rialto or the Chirinale of the already closed National Way, where I have lived so many shared emotions, not to see the cartels drowned by the dust, I turn to the other side.”
